      <body>Hey Jamie, thanks for the patch but render and redirect_to have different semantics, they do not need to accept the same type of arguments. Besides, I usually prefer urls for redirection, it's more explicit. redirect_to :index is not as obvious as redirect_to posts_url.

Finally, the render &quot;new&quot; means: render the template named &quot;new&quot;, notice you don't need to have an action in the controller. Although the render :action =&gt; &quot;new&quot; syntax may cause such confusion.</body>
      <body-html>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Hey Jamie, thanks for the patch but render and redirect_to have
different semantics, they do not need to accept the same type of
arguments. Besides, I usually prefer urls for redirection, it's
more explicit. redirect_to :index is not as obvious as redirect_to
posts_url.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Finally, the render &quot;new&quot; means: render the template named
&quot;new&quot;, notice you don't need to have an action in the controller.
Although the render :action =&amp;gt; &quot;new&quot; syntax may cause such
confusion.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</body-html>
